    "costs": "400000",
    "actions_taken": [
      "Crane boom set in boom rest and placed out of service",
      "BSEE onsite investigation conducted on 26-FEB-2024",
      "Personnel interviews conducted",
      "Load indicator testing verified during annual inspection"
    ],
    "summary": "On 25-FEB-2024 at 0930 hours, a contract construction crew attempted to raise the elevation of an I-beam support by approximately 1 inch on the Talos OCS-G02280 SM 130 B production facility. After unsuccessful attempts with come-along winches, the crew attached the crane's main line to the fixed I-beam and applied tension. The crane operator exceeded the maximum load capacity of 21,500 lbs at the 55-degree boom angle by applying approximately 30,000 lbs of tension, resulting in damage to the crane boom heel section and lattice. Estimated repair cost: $400,000. No injuries occurred.",
    "recommendations": [
      "Ensure crane operators monitor weight indicators while having knowledge of maximum capacity at boom angle",
      "Do not connect or use cranes to lift fixed objects per API RP 2D standards",
      "Conduct comprehensive Job Safety & Environmental Analysis (JSEA) discussing all hazard mitigation methods",
      "Implement stop work procedures when initial lifting attempts fail",
      "Adhere to API RP 2D appendix B C.3.2.3 requirements before starting lifts"
    ],
    "key_phrases": [
      "Load rating exceeded",
      "Fixed object lifting",
      "Boom angle 55 degrees",
      "30,000 lbs tension applied",
      "Maximum capacity 21,500 lbs",
      "Human error",
      "Inadequate JSEA",
      "Stop work failure"
    ]
